                        "content": "The client with a traumatic brain injury (TBI) has begun to excrete copious amounts of dilute urine through the Foley catheter. The client's urine output for the previous shift was 3000 mL. The nurse expects that the primary health care provider will prescribe which medication?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nA complication of TBI is diabetes insipidus, which can occur with insult to the hypothalamus, the antidiuretic hormone storage vesicles, or the posterior pituitary gland. Urine output that exceeds 9 L per day generally requires treatment with desmopressin. Dexamethasone is usually given to control cerebral edema secondary to brain tumors. Ethacrynic acid and mannitol are diuretics, which would be contraindicated.\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nNote the subject, care of the client with a TBI. Recall that a complication of TBI is diabetes insipidus. Knowing that diabetes insipidus results in excretion of large amounts of dilute urine will allow you to eliminate options 1 and 3 immediately because they are diuretics. From the remaining choices, select option 2 because of its action.",
                        "id": "159b027b7f914f1e9fa53e7762c390b7",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "0fc428180ebf4bdfa1377f179abcaa30",
                                "content": "Complaints of chest pain"
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "ae632936b2f2454fa65b4475ceaae905",
                                "content": "Bounding peripheral pulses"
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
